Bug.WithStack:
Refer to the unit test coverage report for more info. Here's a recent report:
http://download.eclipse.org/webtools/committers/drops/I-I200511162235- 200511162235/apiresults/api-javadoc-summary.html The URL is incorrect, but I found the reports. There are several errors in the report, but I'll try to fix the ones that are actually untested API. According to the latest report, there are 24 methods untested: 23 core and 1 UI. Of the 23 core I walked through and found that well over half are false positives in the report. There might be one or two that I am actually missing here, but it is minimal and not a big exposure. The UI method is one that is difficult to test without user interaction (could hang the build) and I do not plan to unit test. Tim, I'm looking at the report right now. Can you give me an example of the false positive?
I notice that the 23 apis in core are apis on interfaces. To get those tested, there must be a corresponding concrete class. Can you tell me the name of the concrete class and in which JUnit testcase this concrete class is tested? This wil help me track down the problem. Thanks. Ok, here's one. The report shows that the following method isn't run: org.eclipse.wst.server.core.IRuntime.isReadOnly()
This is covered via org.eclipse.wst.server.core.tests.ext.AbstractRuntimeTestCase.test0010IsReadOnly(). To confuse you further, this is an abstract test that is run via a concrete impl in the Tomcat tests plugin (org.eclipse.jst.server.tomcat.core.tests.AbstractTomcatRuntimeTestCase). Consider this:
public interface IRuntime {...}
public class Base {...}
public class Runtime extends Base implements IRuntime {...}
The problem is that when the scanner compute the interface-to-concrete-class list, Base.java was not consider to be a concrete implementation of IRuntime.java. Although this is true, it doesn't mean methods on Base.java is not the concrete implementation for methods defined on IRuntime. Thanks for the fix. Closing bug.

